The area

Address
Neighborhood: Parque das Nações
This neighborhood was built up at the end of the 1990s mostly because of the Expo '98. The pavilions and structures that once were the home of all the Expo's attractions and exhibits are still culturally and artistically significant. In Parque das Nações you'll explore conference and concert pavilions, a shopping center, trendy restaurants and an enjoyable cable car ride you can't miss out on. On top of this, the amazing Lisbon Oceanarium (one of the most spectacular things you'll ever see in the city) will take your breath away: its respect and will to preserve natural wildlife is uncanny. Easily accessible by metro, bus or taxi from the city center, Parque das Nações is highly recommended for anyone who'll spend more than 3 days in the Portuguese capital.
How to get there
  • Oriente • 1 min walk
  • Cabo Ruivo • 9 min walk

    Decent station
    Convenient and user friendly, this station has an attached bus station, the excellent metro and long distance trains alongside places to eat, a shopping mall including a large supermarket. Ticket selling staff speak excellent English and guide you through the best type of ticket for your use in Lisbon. There are stairs, escalators and lifts between all floors. Good cover from the rain too when the weather is not the best. Having used the metro and buses in Lisbon over a short stay I would definitely advise in buying a ticket no matter how short your journey. Ticket inspectors frequently patrol and siting opposite is was one passenger who presented a n out of date ticket. His fine was 120€ or 69€ if paid within 15 days. His friend was able to lend him the cash to gain the reduced rate. The ticket prices are very good anyway so there should be no need to avoid paying.

    Got A Bit Dis- Orienting
    We have been to Oriente a few times now but our experience yesterday was out of the ordinary. First of all we didn’t feel information was easy to find at all. Let me explain…due to traffic in Lisbon we missed our train. From that point on I would call this Dis- Orienting station. As we tried to book later tickets there was no large display board showing anything beyond the next few trains. Something like an airport board would be helpful. So we decided to take the Flix bus as that was best time to our home. We tried to book tickets online but their website had problems, tried to discuss with driver, he misdirected us to a ticket machine so we missed that bus. Booked another bus with ticket machine. We had 2 hours to kill but no directory in station re food and shopping choices within station. If our tickets didn’t have where bus position was we wouldn’t have known. How about a centralized board for buses showing departure times and locations? These are all easy fixes and as we live in Portugal would welcome these.

Meowy
Montgomery, AL520 contributions
Not Organized
Sep 2023 • Solo
Took the train from Oriente to Coimbra and back for a weekend trip from Lisbon. The station is on the red line to the airport and to downtown, which is convenient. The rest is not very well organized. It is about 5 levels, with trains being on the top, a waiting area on the 4th floor and a mall being below. There is also a homeless camp on the bottom floor of the station.

It is hard to navigate around as up and down escalators are not near one another. Many people had to either lug their luggage up or down stairs without an escalator. There is very little in the way of information and help if you are new to the station. The trains are also always late. Mine was 2 hours late. I talked to my hotel in Coimbra about it and they confirmed the trains from the station are never on time. Nothing much you can do but grin I guess.
Written October 7, 2023
